Upon the addition of SDBS to CDs-Ru system, the fluorescence quenched of CDs was recovered within 2min. After 2min, the fluorescence signal was stabilized, indicating a fast recovery of the system (Fig. 4
                        ). The fluorescence change of CDs in the presence of SDBS is investigated. According to Fig. 5
                        , the fluorescence intensity of CDs solution containing 2.50μg/mL SDBS at 450nm changes conspicuously. The above result shows that CDs are insensitive to SDBS, and means that the adsorption of SDBS on CDs surface can not change the fluorescence of CDs. At present, surfactant self-assembly structures on carbon surfaces have been extensively studied by molecular simulations [41–43]. It was observed that surfactants with 12 or more methyl groups are able to form hemimicelles at the water–carbon interface at high packing density [44,45]. Thus, mechanism of CDs fluorescence recovery by SDBS may be as follows: upon the addition of SDBS, self-assembly of SDBS on carbon surfaces was formed and competition between Ru and SDBS in surface of CDs occurs. Ru was then able to be removed from the surface of CDs, and thus the fluorescence of the system could be recovered, the probe was thus “turn-on”. With the increased of SDBS concentration, the fluorescence response of CDs-Ru system gradually increases. Therefore, the CDs-Ru system can be explored to probe SDBS.
